04:13.268 --> 04:15.938
We don't have a pulse.
Let's get him to the trauma bay.

04:17.338 --> 04:19.164
Wait, I have to stay with my dad.

04:19.173 --> 04:20.933
No, we need to check you
for injuries first.

04:20.942 --> 04:22.934
- What's your name?
- Eva Garcia, and that's Eli.

04:22.944 --> 04:25.804
- Is my dad dead?
- Nurse Hundley's gonna take care of you.

04:25.814 --> 04:28.106
The doctors are working
on him now, honey.

04:28.116 --> 04:30.909
MINA: I'm leading this code.
This man is in asystole.

04:30.919 --> 04:32.443
Everyone get in line for compressions.

04:32.453 --> 04:34.412
Bai, you're up next.

04:34.422 --> 04:36.013
So much for a quiet night.

04:36.023 --> 04:38.083
- We need access to the airway.
- I'll intubate.

04:38.093 --> 04:40.419
- I'll get access.
- His body temperature is 72 degrees.

04:40.429 --> 04:42.487
None of this matters
if we can't get him warm.

04:42.497 --> 04:44.166
We need heated blankets and warm saline.

04:48.142 --> 04:49.860
I'm having trouble getting the tube in.

04:49.871 --> 04:52.392
I can't get a view.
Let's try succinylcholine.

04:52.403 --> 04:54.605
Maybe that'll help me get the tube in.

04:54.977 --> 04:56.835
ERIK: Excuse me, but if possible,

04:56.845 --> 04:59.235
could I maybe pronounce him dead
when compressions stop?

04:59.246 --> 05:01.486
See, Dr. Pravesh said it's good
for us to practice our skills,

05:01.497 --> 05:04.017
- and I've never had the opportunity...
- Shut your mouth.

05:04.028 --> 05:07.044
Listen, my dad is not dead. He's frozen.

05:07.054 --> 05:09.691
Erik, out.

05:13.160 --> 05:14.730
How's my dad?

05:15.797 --> 05:17.556
Your father's heart has stopped.

05:17.566 --> 05:19.385
- Because he's cold?
- Yes.

05:19.396 --> 05:21.225
His body temperature is dangerously low.

05:21.235 --> 05:23.061
We're hoping, if we warm him up,

05:23.071 --> 05:24.462
his heart will start again.

05:24.472 --> 05:26.131
I know you'll save him.

05:26.141 --> 05:27.677
Promise?

05:28.843 --> 05:30.469
We'll do everything we can.

05:30.479 --> 05:32.236
I expect updates.

05:32.246 --> 05:34.083
(ELI CRYING)

05:36.884 --> 05:39.355
Call Dr. Austin. We need him.

05:47.996 --> 05:49.987
Hundley, I'm four miles away.

05:49.997 --> 05:51.989
Whatever it is, get Dr. Kays.

05:51.999 --> 05:53.991
Kays is on vacation in Florida.

05:54.001 --> 05:58.063
Mina has a patient with severe
hypothermia in cardiac arrest.

05:58.073 --> 06:01.165
Just short of slamming my feet
through the floor of this car

06:01.175 --> 06:03.167
and Fred Flintstone-ing my ass there,

06:03.177 --> 06:05.203
<i>I'm not sure what I can do about it.</i>

06:05.213 --> 06:08.617
Dr. Okafor told me
to tell you she needs you.

06:10.384 --> 06:14.679
Then neither snow nor rain
nor heat nor gloom of night

06:14.689 --> 06:17.749
shall stay this doctor
from the swift completion

06:17.759 --> 06:19.761
of his appointed rounds.

06:25.800 --> 06:27.859
(GRUNTS)

06:27.869 --> 06:30.361
(PANTING)

06:30.371 --> 06:32.631
Scale of one to ten, how's your pain?

06:32.641 --> 06:35.133
(DONNA GRUNTS)

06:35.143 --> 06:37.089
It's a little worse.

06:37.100 --> 06:39.320
But I don't want any more drugs yet,

06:39.331 --> 06:42.905
because I have a visitor coming tomorrow

06:42.916 --> 06:44.909
and I want to have a clear head.

06:44.920 --> 06:48.746
Well, with all the years
you spent working in hospice,

06:48.756 --> 06:51.049
I'm sure you know exactly what you want.

06:51.059 --> 06:52.784
25 years.

06:52.794 --> 06:55.087
If there's one thing
I understand, it's dying.

06:55.097 --> 06:57.888
Uh, when the chemo stopped working,

06:57.898 --> 07:00.258
I signed a "do not resuscitate" order,

07:00.268 --> 07:04.429
so if my heart stops,
no one will give me CPR.

07:04.439 --> 07:06.825
Well, I know you were planning
to get to hospice tonight,

07:06.836 --> 07:08.734
but it looks like you're stuck with us.

07:08.744 --> 07:12.596
What can we do to help?
Your wish is our command.

07:12.607 --> 07:15.941
(BOTH LAUGH)

07:15.951 --> 07:18.275
Oh, just keep me comfortable.

07:18.285 --> 07:19.677
No needle sticks.

07:19.687 --> 07:21.524
Leave me be.

07:22.445 --> 07:23.782
I really admire you.

07:23.792 --> 07:25.562
- Oh...
- I've seen too many people

07:25.573 --> 07:27.919
over-treated and harmed
in their last days.

07:27.929 --> 07:30.455
Yeah, well,
I'm hoping for a few more weeks.

07:30.465 --> 07:31.756
(CHUCKLES)

07:31.766 --> 07:35.626
Do you know, many people
live longer in hospice.

07:35.636 --> 07:38.429
- I did know that.
- (PAGER BEEPING)

07:38.439 --> 07:39.941
Nic's got your back.

07:42.511 --> 07:45.003
DONNA: In hospice, it's
going to be so much nicer.

07:45.013 --> 07:47.606
- NIC: Hmm.
- Scented candles.

07:47.616 --> 07:49.607
"Northern Fir" is my favorite.

07:49.617 --> 07:51.443
I just love the smell of Christmas.

07:51.453 --> 07:53.277
(CHUCKLES) Me, too.

07:53.287 --> 07:55.547
Friends surrounding me,

07:55.557 --> 07:57.549
all of us drinking Tennessee whiskey

07:57.559 --> 07:59.950
and listening to gospel hymns.

07:59.960 --> 08:01.520
Mm.

08:01.530 --> 08:04.455
Okay, enough schmaltz.

08:04.465 --> 08:08.325
I have a juicy audiobook
that's going to put me to sleep.

08:08.335 --> 08:11.797
Oh, and I'll be dreaming
of that last item

08:11.807 --> 08:14.465
that I'm gonna be
checking off my bucket list.

08:14.475 --> 08:18.080
What is that last item you're
checking off your bucket list?

08:19.997 --> 08:21.822
Bob.

08:22.167 --> 08:25.643
Bob's the man,
the visitor that I mentioned.

08:25.691 --> 08:28.561
He was my chance at true love.

08:29.990 --> 08:31.871
After Bob, there was no one.

08:32.840 --> 08:34.518
But you're gonna see him?

08:34.528 --> 08:37.655
(LAUGHS): Yes, I am.

08:37.666 --> 08:40.892
I saw online that he's divorced,

08:40.902 --> 08:45.730
and, um, I wrote him.

08:45.740 --> 08:49.700
And wonder of all wonders,
he's going to come see me.

08:49.710 --> 08:53.571
He would have been here today,
but he was delayed by the storm.

08:53.581 --> 08:55.673
That is amazing, Donna.

08:55.683 --> 08:58.877
Yeah, I haven't seen him for 30 years.

08:58.887 --> 09:00.678
Oh...

09:00.688 --> 09:05.260
Oh, words that were never said
will finally be spoken.

09:06.360 --> 09:09.465
And I will die without regrets.

09:11.032 --> 09:13.090
(CHUCKLES)

09:13.100 --> 09:14.725
<i>BELL: Look, I know I said</i>

09:14.735 --> 09:17.729
all hands on deck, but it's been a
while since my pediatric rotation.

09:18.027 --> 09:19.685
Did you get a hold of Dr. Jonas?

09:19.696 --> 09:20.831
He's busy.

09:21.442 --> 09:22.489
Feldman?

09:22.500 --> 09:24.069
In with the injured paramedics.

09:35.489 --> 09:40.918
So, you kids dug your dad out
of the snow all by yourselves.

09:40.928 --> 09:42.787
How'd you get him in the car, honey?

09:42.797 --> 09:45.891
Well, we put him on the sled,
and we pushed him.

09:45.901 --> 09:48.593
It was dark, and everyone
was gone, so we dragged him

09:48.603 --> 09:51.061
into the car, and I drove straight here.

09:51.071 --> 09:53.565
By yourself? Incredible.

09:53.584 --> 09:56.320
She's very brave. Isn't she, Eli?

09:57.336 --> 09:59.070
EVA: He doesn't talk much,

09:59.080 --> 10:01.339
ever since my mom left.

10:01.349 --> 10:03.340
Do you know how to get in touch
with your mom?

10:03.350 --> 10:07.178
Uh, the judge says
we can't talk to her anymore.

10:07.562 --> 10:09.564
Not for a while, at least.

10:12.760 --> 10:17.254
So, just a few bumps and scrapes on Eli.

10:17.264 --> 10:18.967
- (CHUCKLES)
- So, your turn.

10:18.978 --> 10:21.091
How about I have a look at that wrist?

10:21.101 --> 10:23.094
HUNDLEY: Okay...

10:23.104 --> 10:25.340
(MONITOR BEEPING)

10:28.375 --> 10:30.816
MINA: He's not warming up
fast enough from fluids.

10:30.827 --> 10:32.604
The quickest way
is to circulate warm blood.

10:32.614 --> 10:34.850
- He needs to go on bypass.
- Let's get him into the OR.

10:43.524 --> 10:46.051
Hey, hey, hey, wait, wait, wait.
Is my dad's heart beating now?

10:46.061 --> 10:48.018
Uh, not yet. Uh, we're working on it.

10:48.028 --> 10:50.032
I know you'll save his life.

10:52.834 --> 10:55.037
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS, DOORS SLIDE OPEN)

11:06.380 --> 11:08.384
(PHONE RINGING)

11:10.752 --> 11:13.845
(PANTING)

11:13.855 --> 11:15.846
(BEEP)

11:15.856 --> 11:18.816
You do realize I'm doing
my damnedest to get there

11:18.826 --> 11:20.484
even though I'm freezing to death.

11:20.494 --> 11:23.220
I'm about to scrub in,
and there's no attending here.

11:23.230 --> 11:25.824
You have operated
without an attending before.

11:25.834 --> 11:27.893
I'm two miles out.

11:27.903 --> 11:30.339
(PANTING)

11:31.739 --> 11:34.666
I am in the initial stages of frostbite.

11:34.676 --> 11:37.234
I'd prefer not to lose my fingertips.

11:37.244 --> 11:39.037
(EXHALES) What's the procedure?

11:39.047 --> 11:42.046
I'm setting up femoral cannulation
for bypass to help him rewarm.

11:42.057 --> 11:43.615
<i>Are you serious right now?</i>

11:43.626 --> 11:46.153
<i>You can put a patient on bypass
in your sleep.</i>

11:46.164 --> 11:48.545
Start without me. Finish without me.

11:48.556 --> 11:50.047
<i>But what if there's complications?</i>

11:50.057 --> 11:52.450
Dissection. Pseudoaneurysm.
Limb ischemia.

11:52.460 --> 11:53.884
<i>Mina,</i>

11:53.894 --> 11:55.787
are you afraid to fly solo?

11:56.628 --> 11:58.123
I am not afraid.

11:58.133 --> 11:59.778
Well, you should be.

12:01.372 --> 12:02.893
Fear makes us careful.

12:02.903 --> 12:04.796
It's a good thing.

12:04.806 --> 12:06.931
But never let it paralyze you.

12:07.879 --> 12:09.329
It's a dad.

12:09.953 --> 12:12.201
He's frozen. He's in cardiac arrest.

12:12.212 --> 12:14.283
He has two little kids.

12:15.898 --> 12:17.742
The little girl is very brave.

12:17.752 --> 12:20.422
She reminds me of my sisters.

12:21.422 --> 12:23.248
(EXHALES)

12:23.258 --> 12:25.082
All right.

12:25.092 --> 12:27.719
As soon as my extremities warm up,

12:27.729 --> 12:29.255
I will head back out.

12:30.443 --> 12:32.134
But you got this, Okafor.

12:33.100 --> 12:34.602
(BEEP)

12:37.605 --> 12:39.173
(WATER RUNNING)

12:50.818 --> 12:51.847
Hey.

12:52.253 --> 12:53.628
What are you doing here?

12:53.639 --> 12:56.865
Look, I-I know I messed up
in the ER, and I'm so sorry.

12:56.876 --> 12:58.983
But the kids aren't down here anymore,

12:58.994 --> 13:01.418
and I'd still like to practice
the death exam.

13:01.428 --> 13:04.465
You realize we aren't talking
about an item on a checklist.

13:05.075 --> 13:06.257
It's a person.

13:06.267 --> 13:08.926
- A father. A young man.
- No, I-I understand that.

13:09.792 --> 13:11.467
But I'm just a first-year med student.

13:11.478 --> 13:13.103
I don't get that much
time in a hospital.

13:13.114 --> 13:14.667
And I haven't seen
that many dead people;

13:14.678 --> 13:17.167
only my cadaver in anatomy lab. Ernest.

13:17.177 --> 13:19.771
I named him Ernest
to remind me of his humanity

13:19.781 --> 13:23.484
and also to say, "We were
working in dead earnest."

13:25.052 --> 13:26.878
<i>WOMAN (OVER P.A.):
Triage nurse to the ER.</i>

13:26.888 --> 13:28.958
<i>- Triage nurse to the ER.
- Come here.</i>

13:30.859 --> 13:33.128
Quit hanging around here
like the angel of death, Erik.

13:34.539 --> 13:37.343
I might have something you
can help me with later tonight.

13:47.709 --> 13:49.533
(EVA HISSES, GROANS)

13:49.543 --> 13:51.702
Careful.

13:51.712 --> 13:52.970
That's got to hurt.

13:52.980 --> 13:54.839
Yeah. I think it's broken.

13:54.849 --> 13:56.407
I think you're right.

13:56.417 --> 13:58.375
We're gonna take a picture. Don't move.

13:58.385 --> 14:00.154
Okay.

14:01.755 --> 14:03.181
See you've made a friend.

14:03.191 --> 14:05.082
Yeah, it's not clear what he sees in me.

14:05.092 --> 14:07.085
But they're great kids.

14:07.095 --> 14:10.220
It's kind of hard to resist 'em.
Not one word of complaint.

14:10.230 --> 14:11.800
All they do is ask about their father.

14:13.834 --> 14:15.258
You want to take 'em for a while?

14:15.269 --> 14:16.694
I'd love to.

14:16.704 --> 14:19.531
But as soon as I set Eva's
wrist, I have to go to the ER.

14:19.541 --> 14:21.766
Our paramedic has a dislocated hip.

14:21.776 --> 14:24.002
It's all on you, Dr. Bell.

14:24.012 --> 14:26.047
(BEEPING)

14:30.018 --> 14:31.341
Okay, you ready?

14:31.351 --> 14:33.244
(SLURRING): So ready.

14:33.254 --> 14:35.580
This guy is flying high.

14:35.590 --> 14:38.016
You are gonna feel this nonetheless.

14:38.026 --> 14:39.917
But I'm not gonna care.

14:39.927 --> 14:41.351
Do it.

14:41.361 --> 14:44.022
Okay. In three.

14:44.032 --> 14:46.023
- One... two...
- (PAINED GROAN)

14:46.033 --> 14:47.859
(SHARP EXHALE)

14:47.869 --> 14:50.595
(LAUGHS)

14:50.605 --> 14:53.630
I think we overshot on those meds.

14:53.640 --> 14:55.247
Do we have any left?

14:55.258 --> 14:58.734
(LAUGHING): You didn't say three!

14:58.745 --> 15:00.370
-(GROANS) -(LAUGHING)

15:00.380 --> 15:01.638
All right.

15:01.648 --> 15:03.641
(MOANS SOFTLY)

15:03.651 --> 15:06.244
I came in and found her like this.

15:06.254 --> 15:08.779
She's delirious, maybe septic,
and she's in pain.

15:08.789 --> 15:09.980
Donna?

15:09.991 --> 15:11.249
(YELPS, INHALES SHARPLY)

15:11.259 --> 15:12.908
- (DONNA GROANING)
- Could be a perforation.

15:12.919 --> 15:14.940
What do you want to do? Up the morphine?

15:15.216 --> 15:17.296
Let's give her two milligrams
and get her up to CT.

15:17.307 --> 15:18.422
She's DNR.

15:18.432 --> 15:20.258
DNR doesn't mean "do not treat."

15:20.268 --> 15:23.304
A scan could show if there's something
we could do to buy her some time.

15:29.677 --> 15:31.010
What happened?

15:31.021 --> 15:33.905
(EXHALES) Donna was in pain and altered.

15:34.014 --> 15:36.317
She almost fell off the bed
when I touched her belly.

15:41.355 --> 15:43.348
Looks like a strangulated hernia.

15:43.358 --> 15:45.149
Which we could fix in surgery.

15:45.159 --> 15:47.417
Did Donna say she wanted surgery?

15:47.427 --> 15:49.821
I mean, she's in and out
of consciousness.

15:49.831 --> 15:53.423
She can't make decisions for herself.
But I do know...

15:53.433 --> 15:56.194
she wants to stay alive for Bob.

15:56.204 --> 15:58.196
Who's Bob?

15:58.206 --> 15:59.998
Remember the visitor Donna
was talking about?

16:00.008 --> 16:01.465
- Mm-hmm.
- Well, after you left,

16:01.475 --> 16:03.100
she told me his name was Bob.

16:03.110 --> 16:04.835
He was the love of her life.

16:04.845 --> 16:06.537
She hasn't seen him in decades,

16:06.547 --> 16:08.940
- and he's finally on his way.
- (SIGHS)

16:08.950 --> 16:12.676
Okay, but we have her wishes in writing.

16:12.686 --> 16:14.112
Her advanced directives says

16:14.122 --> 16:15.680
she wants no major interventions.

16:15.690 --> 16:18.300
And I get that, but you didn't
hear what I heard.

16:18.311 --> 16:20.125
And if she doesn't have this surgery,

16:20.136 --> 16:21.485
she might not make it through the night.

16:21.495 --> 16:23.321
Surgery could have complications.

16:23.331 --> 16:25.732
She could end up stuck in the
hospital tethered to machines.

16:25.743 --> 16:28.493
Donna's health care proxy needs
to be making these decisions.

16:28.503 --> 16:30.195
- Have you reached her?
- I've tried.

16:30.205 --> 16:32.729
Several times. The phones
must be down from the storm.

16:32.739 --> 16:34.132
(CONRAD SIGHS)

16:34.142 --> 16:36.011
So, if there's no proxy,
I have to decide.

16:38.145 --> 16:40.748
She goes back to her room on pain meds.

16:43.383 --> 16:45.742
And I think we should try to fix this,

16:45.753 --> 16:47.823
so we disagree.

16:49.582 --> 16:52.150
I'm her doctor. This is my decision.

16:52.160 --> 16:53.464
You're pulling rank?

16:53.475 --> 16:56.054
I'm saying the burden is on me.

16:56.064 --> 16:59.190
And Donna explicitly decided to be DNR.

16:59.200 --> 17:01.825
- I have to uphold that.
- And I believe we should

17:01.835 --> 17:04.261
uphold the wishes
that she made clear to me.

17:04.271 --> 17:05.662
I hear you.

17:05.672 --> 17:08.022
And as painful as this is
for both of us,

17:08.034 --> 17:11.137
I believe that we have to
uphold the written directive.

17:12.417 --> 17:14.555
She's going back to her room.

17:27.095 --> 17:29.230
(SIGHS)

17:33.901 --> 17:36.193
♪ ♪

17:36.203 --> 17:38.028
JESSICA: Flawless procedure, Dr. O.

17:38.038 --> 17:39.564
Well done.

17:39.574 --> 17:41.434
CHU: Body temp is up to 80 degrees.

17:41.445 --> 17:43.265
MINA: Still no heart rhythm.

17:43.443 --> 17:45.292
CHU: How long do we wait?

17:45.303 --> 17:47.938
I'll let you know...
once I've figure that out.

17:51.054 --> 17:53.824
I heard Eva's quite
the little boss. (CHUCKLES)

17:56.156 --> 17:58.249
I really like that kid.

17:58.259 --> 18:00.884
Wh... Seriously, Dr. Okafor? (CHUCKLES)

18:00.894 --> 18:02.987
I really like kids.

18:03.347 --> 18:04.950
Especially that one.

18:06.469 --> 18:08.772
BAI: His temperature is up to 83.

18:11.072 --> 18:12.641
84...

18:14.174 --> 18:15.499
We have a rhythm.

18:15.509 --> 18:18.068
- Eva was right.
- (JESSICA LAUGHS)

18:18.078 --> 18:19.447
Her father is not dead.

18:22.616 --> 18:24.608
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

18:24.618 --> 18:26.611
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

18:26.621 --> 18:28.011
All right.

18:28.021 --> 18:29.747
(GRUNTS)

18:29.757 --> 18:31.114
This is Atlanta.

18:31.124 --> 18:32.683
It's not Chicago.

18:32.693 --> 18:35.018
Let's go, baby.

18:35.028 --> 18:38.099
- (PANTING)
- (WIND HOWLING)

18:48.776 --> 18:51.469
<i>- Go!
- (YELLS)</i>

18:51.479 --> 18:53.470
<i>Ah. I'm doing it!</i>

18:53.480 --> 18:55.539
<i>Dad, Dad, I'm doing it!</i>

18:55.549 --> 18:57.475
(LAUGHS) You know,

18:57.485 --> 19:00.111
he couldn't ride that bike
until Dad put the cape on him.

19:00.121 --> 19:01.845
(EVA GIGGLES)

19:01.855 --> 19:04.315
Dad proved you're a superhero,
didn't he?

19:04.325 --> 19:06.284
<i>ELI (ON VIDEO): I did it. Yeah!</i>

19:06.294 --> 19:07.985
EVA: Come on. Doctors...

19:07.995 --> 19:09.720
they can be superheroes, too.

19:09.730 --> 19:13.357
Doctor Strange, he's a neurosurgeon.

19:13.367 --> 19:16.393
The Hulk... is a doctor.

19:16.403 --> 19:19.229
BELL: Yeah, I like the Hulk.

19:19.239 --> 19:21.188
I always did. I...

19:22.104 --> 19:24.342
When I was your age...

19:25.078 --> 19:26.748
I wanted to be the Hulk.

19:27.914 --> 19:30.051
- Really?
- Yeah.

19:32.153 --> 19:34.211
- (CHUCKLES)
- (LIGHT KNOCKING)

19:34.221 --> 19:35.813
- Yeah?
- Dr. Bell, do you have a second?

19:35.823 --> 19:37.259
Okay.

19:43.597 --> 19:45.489
CONRAD: You have a fever.

19:45.499 --> 19:47.424
You may have an infection.

19:47.434 --> 19:50.027
- From what?
- The dialysis line

19:50.037 --> 19:52.095
can be an entry point for bacteria.

19:52.105 --> 19:53.998
It's a common complication.

19:54.008 --> 19:55.400
(JESSIE EXHALES)

19:55.410 --> 19:57.211
All right, let's have a look.

19:58.679 --> 20:00.337
- (GROANS)
- Yeah.

20:00.347 --> 20:02.006
There is a little erythema there.

20:02.016 --> 20:03.727
We'll get a set of blood cultures

20:03.738 --> 20:05.408
before we start you on antibiotics.

20:08.076 --> 20:10.680
I didn't ask Dr. Shaw to treat me.

20:13.728 --> 20:15.353
He's a good doctor.

20:15.363 --> 20:17.188
Maybe.

20:17.198 --> 20:20.124
- I prefer you.
- (CHUCKLES)

20:20.134 --> 20:22.125
So does Nic.

20:22.135 --> 20:23.704
I know that.

20:27.040 --> 20:29.577
- So how are you doing? Really?
- (JESSIE CHUCKLES)

20:31.578 --> 20:34.070
I'm just tired.

20:34.080 --> 20:36.807
This is all like a bad dream.

20:36.817 --> 20:39.977
It'll be over, and...

20:39.987 --> 20:42.157
I'm gonna stay sober this time.

20:43.490 --> 20:45.450
My dad's back.

20:45.460 --> 20:48.152
My family's together again.

20:48.162 --> 20:50.988
We can start over.

20:50.998 --> 20:54.291
And my kidneys will get better... right?

20:54.301 --> 20:55.992
Well...

20:56.002 --> 20:58.229
there's no reason not to be optimistic.

20:58.239 --> 21:00.597
Whatever's ahead...

21:00.607 --> 21:03.267
we'll deal with it.

21:03.277 --> 21:05.279
Okay. (SNIFFLES)

21:12.353 --> 21:14.089
Get some rest.

21:17.290 --> 21:18.835
(SIGHS)

21:18.846 --> 21:20.918
NIC: Nolan said that he can
do it laproscopically,

21:20.928 --> 21:22.704
but because Donna can't make
decisions for herself,

21:22.715 --> 21:24.588
we just need a second physician
to sign off...

21:24.598 --> 21:26.356
Surgery is not gonna cure
her colon cancer.

21:26.366 --> 21:28.325
She's got a DNR,
and she's going to hospice.

21:28.335 --> 21:29.985
And normally I would agree, 100%,

21:29.996 --> 21:32.397
but, based off a conversation
that I had with Donna,

21:32.408 --> 21:34.678
I really believe she wants
to make it through the night.

21:35.509 --> 21:36.666
Why?

21:36.676 --> 21:38.309
(EXHALES)

21:39.012 --> 21:42.006
She's waiting on
a very important visitor

21:42.016 --> 21:43.975
who's just been held up by the storm.

21:43.985 --> 21:46.544
Look, I have been with Donna
through years of chemo.

21:46.554 --> 21:48.613
I know her, and I really think

21:48.623 --> 21:50.047
that she would want to go through

21:50.057 --> 21:51.460
with this surgery if she could.

21:53.160 --> 21:54.662
Is she insured?

21:55.598 --> 21:57.961
Are you asking if the surgery's covered?

21:57.972 --> 21:59.753
Yeah. Sorry, that's my job.

21:59.764 --> 22:01.625
CEO, fiscal responsibility.

22:01.635 --> 22:05.215
(SIGHS) Medicare and supplementals,
so yes, fully covered.

22:06.284 --> 22:07.753
I'll sign off.

22:09.710 --> 22:12.068
You know, better yet,
this is gonna be simple.

22:12.078 --> 22:14.037
It's gonna be in and out
in under an hour.

22:14.048 --> 22:15.349
I'll do the surgery myself.

22:17.183 --> 22:18.564
(CLAPS HANDS TOGETHER)

22:18.575 --> 22:20.472
- Okay.
- (EXHALES)

22:20.483 --> 22:21.818
We're going somewhere.

22:23.089 --> 22:25.092
(WHOOPING, EXCITED CHATTER)

22:28.028 --> 22:30.520
What in the name of God is going on?

22:30.530 --> 22:32.480
They're playing
med student bowling, Dr. Bell.

22:32.491 --> 22:36.052
You're not kindergarteners. How many
children are there in this hospital?

22:36.063 --> 22:37.932
Give them some scut to do.

22:39.351 --> 22:40.574
Kit.

22:40.585 --> 22:42.066
- Hi.
- Just who I'm looking for.

22:42.076 --> 22:44.242
I have a surgery. Are you free now

22:44.253 --> 22:45.670
- to take care of these kids?
- Sure.

22:45.680 --> 22:48.573
- No. No.
- I... you know, I'm...

22:48.583 --> 22:50.040
I'm gonna tell you a secret.

22:50.050 --> 22:53.277
Dr. Voss has superpowers

22:53.287 --> 22:55.056
even stronger than mine.

22:56.390 --> 22:58.114
I do.

22:58.124 --> 23:00.250
I...

23:00.260 --> 23:03.086
break bones and put them back together.

23:03.096 --> 23:05.355
BELL: So, if you go with her

23:05.365 --> 23:08.603
for a little while, she can show you.

23:11.238 --> 23:13.074
Come on, kids, let's go.

23:16.443 --> 23:19.069
(QUIETLY): Okay. Thank you.

23:19.079 --> 23:20.770
Let's get something to eat, shall we?

23:20.780 --> 23:22.272
You must be starving.

23:22.282 --> 23:24.575
KIT: It's been a long day.

23:24.585 --> 23:26.787
I'm just putting it back.

23:30.557 --> 23:32.383
He looks like my dad.

23:32.393 --> 23:33.950
You said you wanted to do this.

23:33.960 --> 23:35.419
We have to confirm that he's dead.

23:35.429 --> 23:36.631
Start the death exam, please.

23:39.467 --> 23:41.992
He's warm. I thought he'd be cold.

23:42.002 --> 23:44.129
He looks kind of alive.
This is freaking me out.

23:44.140 --> 23:45.242
What happened to this guy?

23:46.926 --> 23:48.798
Cardiac amyloidosis.

23:48.808 --> 23:51.980
Restrictive cardiomyopathy.
Heart failure.

23:53.146 --> 23:54.672
Impressive you know that.

23:54.682 --> 23:56.740
I want to be a cardiologist.

23:56.750 --> 23:58.575
My grandpa died young of a heart attack.

23:58.585 --> 24:00.577
My dad had a heart attack
last year, but...

24:00.587 --> 24:03.325
he's okay now.

24:05.860 --> 24:07.450
Whoa, whoa, whoa. You all right?

24:07.460 --> 24:09.819
Okay. Sit.

24:09.829 --> 24:11.298
Head between your knees.

24:15.462 --> 24:17.420
ERIK: Been an idiot.

24:18.133 --> 24:20.344
Can't declare a guy dead.

24:22.055 --> 24:23.444
Can you do it?

24:24.778 --> 24:25.960
I can.

24:26.811 --> 24:29.040
But you'll have to watch
so you can learn, okay?

24:34.772 --> 24:36.490
No heart sounds.

24:42.852 --> 24:44.992
Pupils are fixed and dilated.

25:03.584 --> 25:05.653
Go on.

25:09.256 --> 25:10.479
ERIK: Time of death:

25:11.208 --> 25:13.444
2:41 a.m.

25:18.789 --> 25:20.853
JESSICA: We're sending
you a 42-year-old man,

25:20.864 --> 25:22.660
presented in full arrest, now rewarmed

25:22.670 --> 25:25.863
with normal sinus rhythm
and stable blood pressure.

25:25.873 --> 25:27.178
So we're done here?

25:27.189 --> 25:29.314
Uh, since his temp is back to normal...

25:29.325 --> 25:31.101
BAI: My feet are killing me.

25:31.112 --> 25:34.604
And triceps are hurting from
doing all those compressions.

25:34.614 --> 25:35.683
Don't be a whiner.

25:38.085 --> 25:40.185
Let's get him ready for transport.

25:41.299 --> 25:43.556
- (MONITOR ALARM BEEPING)
- His pressure's dropping.

25:44.691 --> 25:47.050
- MINA: I'll do a quick exam.
- CHU: I'm gonna give him

25:47.060 --> 25:48.853
a liter wide open
and start him on pressors.

25:48.863 --> 25:50.220
His heart sounds muffled.

25:50.230 --> 25:52.123
And distended neck veins.

25:52.133 --> 25:54.592
Bai, pass me an echo probe.

25:54.602 --> 25:56.360
Where's the Raptor?

25:56.370 --> 25:57.972
Is he here yet?

26:12.585 --> 26:15.589
(MONITOR BEEPING)

26:29.002 --> 26:31.729
- How's it going?
- BELL: Not gonna be so simple.

26:31.739 --> 26:34.097
There are a lot of adhesions
from prior surgeries.

26:34.107 --> 26:36.143
Gonna take a while to work through them.

26:41.347 --> 26:43.339
Oh, wait. That's dead bowel.

26:43.349 --> 26:45.075
I'm gonna have to do a bowel resection.

26:45.085 --> 26:46.954
There's no way I can do this
laparoscopically.

26:49.323 --> 26:51.981
Look, if this could end
with her unable to control

26:51.991 --> 26:55.318
the end of her life,
then you need to stop now.

26:55.328 --> 26:57.954
You asked me to bring her here.

26:57.964 --> 27:00.240
Now I'm gonna do everything I can

27:00.251 --> 27:03.027
to make sure she gets
off this table alive.

27:03.037 --> 27:05.695
I'm not gonna have her die in my OR.

27:05.705 --> 27:07.875
Convert to open. 10 blade.

27:17.617 --> 27:19.343
MINA: Raptor isn't here.

27:19.353 --> 27:21.211
JESSICA: I can't even
get him on the phone.

27:21.221 --> 27:22.680
Cell service is down.

27:22.690 --> 27:24.614
So, what do we do?

27:24.624 --> 27:26.816
I am making a pericardial window

27:26.826 --> 27:28.818
to drain the blood
from around the heart.

27:28.828 --> 27:32.288
The sledding accident must have
caused some traumatic injury.

27:32.298 --> 27:34.858
CHU: Which started to bleed
as we rewarmed him on bypass.

27:35.766 --> 27:38.319
MINA: The pericardium is
completely filled with blood.

27:38.330 --> 27:39.565
15 blade.

27:40.406 --> 27:42.165
Draining the pericardium.

27:42.175 --> 27:43.700
(BAI GASPS)

27:43.710 --> 27:47.182
(MONITOR BEEPING)

27:48.551 --> 27:52.008
He's bleeding too much. I need to
open up his chest to control it.

27:52.018 --> 27:53.320
Sternal saw.

27:54.755 --> 27:56.713
What's going on?

27:56.723 --> 27:58.181
Shouldn't we wait for Dr. Austin?

27:58.191 --> 27:59.717
This man could die if we don't proceed.

27:59.727 --> 28:01.018
Give me the saw!

28:01.028 --> 28:03.687
CHU: Activate massive
transfusion protocol.

28:03.697 --> 28:06.701
(SAW BUZZING)

28:23.683 --> 28:25.286
Take it easy, man. Thank you.

28:29.547 --> 28:31.683
No injuries to the atria or ventricles.

28:32.860 --> 28:33.950
We're losing him.

28:33.960 --> 28:35.563
I can't find the source of bleed.

28:44.939 --> 28:47.141
Okay. Tear in the proximal P.A. Clamp.

28:54.592 --> 28:55.995
Suture.

29:06.579 --> 29:10.286
The Raptor has arrived! Where are we?

29:10.297 --> 29:12.588
Bit late. We've already started closing.

29:12.598 --> 29:14.557
He was in cardiac tamponade.

29:14.567 --> 29:16.326
Mina had to perform
a pericardial window.

29:16.336 --> 29:17.995
Then she had to open him up

29:18.005 --> 29:20.331
and repair a potentially fatal bleed.

29:20.341 --> 29:21.798
It was awesome.

29:21.808 --> 29:24.912
(AUSTIN PANTING)

29:28.378 --> 29:29.609
AUSTIN: So...

29:30.155 --> 29:33.743
you're telling me
that you didn't need me?

29:35.743 --> 29:36.977
Sorry.

29:37.696 --> 29:39.661
(PANTING)

29:42.552 --> 29:44.353
(LAUGHING)

29:44.797 --> 29:46.623
(LAUGHING): I love that.

29:46.633 --> 29:50.427
I... I love that.

29:50.437 --> 29:52.496
See? I told you.

29:53.212 --> 29:54.765
Yes.

29:54.775 --> 29:56.467
Fist bump to Okafor.

29:56.477 --> 29:59.647
(CONTINUES LAUGHING)

30:10.490 --> 30:12.482
You got Bell to take Donna to the OR?

30:12.492 --> 30:13.883
I asked Nolan. Bell took over.

30:13.893 --> 30:15.652
It was supposed to be a simple procedure

30:15.662 --> 30:17.646
to help with her pain
and get her back to hospice.

30:17.657 --> 30:21.525
- She didn't even want a blood draw!
- She was in pain, and it was fixable.

30:21.535 --> 30:22.804
I made the call.

30:25.204 --> 30:26.329
(MONITOR ALARM BEEPING)

30:26.339 --> 30:28.306
She's about to go into cardiac arrest.

30:28.317 --> 30:31.020
- Are we coding her?
- Yes, we are.

30:33.069 --> 30:35.633
No. No, she's DNR.
You got to let her go.

30:35.644 --> 30:36.881
This isn't what she asked for.

30:38.240 --> 30:40.320
- She's in cardiac arrest.
- Damn it!

30:44.924 --> 30:46.594
(BELL GRUNTING)

30:51.198 --> 30:54.357
A death in his OR
will go on Bell's stats.

30:54.367 --> 30:56.360
He'll do anything to avoid that.

30:56.370 --> 30:57.691
Get the defibrillator.

30:57.702 --> 30:59.195
Dr. Bell, stop.

30:59.212 --> 31:00.914
You have to stop.

31:11.010 --> 31:12.875
<i>ERIK: Abductor pollicis,</i>

31:13.600 --> 31:15.659
flexor pollicis brevis...

31:15.670 --> 31:17.205
Big exam?

31:18.224 --> 31:21.184
Um, these hand muscles
are impossible to remember.

31:21.194 --> 31:24.254
"All for one and one for all."

31:24.264 --> 31:25.721
It's a mnemonic.

31:25.731 --> 31:27.282
It helps.

31:30.804 --> 31:32.132
Are you all right?

31:36.943 --> 31:39.970
I always thought of myself
as a... a hero.

31:39.980 --> 31:41.525
Saving lives.

31:42.884 --> 31:44.385
I didn't even think about death.

31:45.751 --> 31:47.888
Death is terrifying.

31:49.772 --> 31:51.315
BUT HERE'S THE THING, ERIK:

31:51.325 --> 31:52.915
You're gonna see a lot of it.

31:52.925 --> 31:56.252
Our job is to hold it off
as long as possible

31:56.262 --> 32:00.401
while never losing sight of the fact
that it is a natural part of life.

32:05.139 --> 32:07.809
(STEADY BREATHING)

32:14.515 --> 32:16.984
(MONITOR BEEPING RAPIDLY)

32:22.756 --> 32:24.914
His temperature's 105.

32:24.924 --> 32:27.683
- He's tachycardic and hypertensive.
- End tidal CO2 is high.

32:27.693 --> 32:29.853
The urine in his Foley,
it's the color of cola.

32:29.863 --> 32:30.988
Hey, what's going on?

32:30.998 --> 32:32.355
MINA: His fever shot up.

32:32.365 --> 32:33.901
His heart rate is sky high.

32:34.968 --> 32:36.392
His limbs are rigid.

32:36.403 --> 32:37.876
AUSTIN: Sounds like a drug reaction.

32:37.887 --> 32:39.829
- What have we given him?
- I'm checking right now.

32:39.839 --> 32:41.632
Epinephrine, heparin, succinylcholine...

32:41.642 --> 32:43.767
MINA: Stop. That's it. He
was given succs in the ER.

32:43.777 --> 32:45.268
His temp was so low it probably caused

32:45.278 --> 32:48.172
- his metabolism to dramatically slow.
- So, once he warmed up in the OR,

32:48.182 --> 32:50.106
he started to metabolize the drug,

32:50.116 --> 32:51.708
causing this rare reaction.

32:51.718 --> 32:53.187
Malignant hyperthermia.

32:53.198 --> 32:55.112
He's literally gone from dying
by being too cold

32:55.122 --> 32:57.858
- to dying by being too hot.
- Well, let's treat him with dantrolene.

32:57.869 --> 33:00.450
That helps, but the problem is, we need
to get his temperature down quick.

33:00.460 --> 33:01.817
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

33:01.827 --> 33:03.730
(QUIET CHATTER)

33:05.332 --> 33:06.989
More snow.

33:06.999 --> 33:09.559
Looks like you did come to the rescue.

33:09.569 --> 33:11.127
MAN: Got it?

33:11.137 --> 33:12.863
AUSTIN: His temperature is 105.

33:12.873 --> 33:14.331
Hurry it up, people.

33:14.341 --> 33:15.843
Pack the snow all around his body.

33:17.510 --> 33:19.169
Hey, how can we help?

33:19.179 --> 33:20.737
Hey, more troops.

33:20.747 --> 33:23.149
We're building a snow angel.
Why don't you pitch in.

33:24.518 --> 33:26.234
Let's hope this works.

33:27.320 --> 33:29.089
(BEEPING)

33:39.466 --> 33:41.803
- You guys good?
- Yeah.

33:49.275 --> 33:51.667
Her blood cultures came back.
Her catheter was infected.

33:51.678 --> 33:53.770
Conrad was right.

33:53.780 --> 33:56.205
I need a new one placed,
but for now, I'll finish

33:56.215 --> 33:58.341
the course of antibiotics you started.

33:58.351 --> 33:59.549
That'll take care of it.

34:00.786 --> 34:02.556
Well, thanks for checking in.

34:14.382 --> 34:16.092
Okay, are you gonna say it,

34:16.103 --> 34:18.428
- or are you gonna make me say it?
- Say what?

34:19.282 --> 34:23.965
Nic, the man with the hair
and the eyes...

34:23.976 --> 34:25.435
he wants you.

34:25.445 --> 34:27.235
Maybe you should worry
about your kidneys.

34:27.246 --> 34:30.373
I am, but my kidneys are so boring
compared to your love life.

34:30.384 --> 34:31.975
- (NIC CHUCKLES)
- Come on, tell me.

34:31.985 --> 34:33.076
Spill. What's going on?

34:33.085 --> 34:36.045
Look, I... I need Alec.

34:36.056 --> 34:39.649
The clinic needs Alec.
The patients need Alec.

34:39.659 --> 34:41.650
You're using him.

34:41.661 --> 34:44.553
I'm being pragmatic.

34:44.563 --> 34:47.322
Totally. I'm impressed.

34:47.333 --> 34:49.625
Hey, if you're into
the hair and the eyes,

34:49.635 --> 34:51.293
I can totally send him your direction.

34:51.304 --> 34:53.795
(LAUGHS) Oh, yeah.
Nothing turns a guy on

34:53.806 --> 34:56.422
like getting to second base
with a girl's catheter.

34:56.433 --> 34:58.168
(NIC CHUCKLES)

35:07.920 --> 35:09.613
CONRAD: She's off the vent.

35:09.623 --> 35:12.683
Off pressors. Breathing on her own.

35:12.693 --> 35:15.363
Vitals are stable.

35:21.967 --> 35:23.837
Donna.

35:25.204 --> 35:26.885
Hey.

35:28.108 --> 35:31.868
- I am so happy you're awake.
- Ah.

35:31.878 --> 35:34.671
(SIGHS)

35:34.681 --> 35:37.050
Look who's doing great.

35:38.851 --> 35:40.544
DONNA: What happened?

35:40.554 --> 35:42.706
CONRAD: You had a strangulated
hernia, and surgery

35:42.717 --> 35:46.013
was the only way to keep you
from dying in the hospital.

35:47.196 --> 35:48.732
We took a chance.

35:50.396 --> 35:52.555
Been so worried we did the wrong thing.

35:53.230 --> 35:55.359
Well, you kind of did.

35:56.308 --> 36:00.072
It might have been easier
if I just never woke up.

36:01.307 --> 36:04.334
But I know you were only trying to do

36:04.344 --> 36:06.902
what you thought was right for me.

36:06.912 --> 36:08.748
I do respect that.

36:10.514 --> 36:14.243
Besides, now I get to go to hospice,

36:14.941 --> 36:16.479
see Bob again.

36:16.490 --> 36:19.482
NIC (CHUCKLES): You just saying
that to make me feel better?

36:19.492 --> 36:21.517
Mm, maybe.

36:21.527 --> 36:23.687
(LAUGHTER)

36:24.550 --> 36:27.233
Well... maybe not.

36:30.570 --> 36:33.763
Ah, sun's rising,
the storm's over, so...

36:33.773 --> 36:35.665
we can get you to hospice now.

36:35.675 --> 36:37.611
(CELL PHONE CHIMES)

36:40.614 --> 36:42.071
Not yet.

36:42.081 --> 36:44.184
Donna has a visitor.

36:45.351 --> 36:46.786
Oh.

36:56.929 --> 36:58.421
How is he?

36:59.188 --> 37:03.025
Still unconscious,
but his vitals are stable.

37:03.804 --> 37:06.139
If he wakes up,
he could have brain damage.

37:07.773 --> 37:09.966
Look, you guys did all you could.

37:09.976 --> 37:11.801
But did we do too much?

37:11.811 --> 37:15.315
We had to try...
for him and his children.

37:24.870 --> 37:26.848
Mr. Garcia?

37:27.395 --> 37:30.921
I am Dr. Okafor. You're at
Chastain Memorial Hospital.

37:30.931 --> 37:33.900
You were in an accident,
but you're all right.

37:39.005 --> 37:41.909
Don't worry, we'll remove
the breathing tube. Okay?

37:44.509 --> 37:47.694
Eva and Eli are fine.
They can't wait to see you.

37:48.443 --> 37:50.443
♪ ♪

38:05.663 --> 38:06.968
Good morning.

38:07.934 --> 38:09.303
Morning.

38:17.644 --> 38:19.780
How's my dad?

38:23.115 --> 38:24.941
How about we go see him?

38:24.951 --> 38:27.157
(LAUGHTER)

38:29.249 --> 38:30.522
EVA: Thank you.

38:31.324 --> 38:33.059
All right, come on. Let's go.

38:35.048 --> 38:36.520
Here we are.

38:36.748 --> 38:38.279
EVA AND ELI: Daddy!

38:42.626 --> 38:44.527
MR. GARCIA: It's okay now.

38:44.537 --> 38:46.574
We're okay.

38:49.615 --> 38:51.084
Thank you.

38:52.032 --> 38:53.969
For taking good care of them.

38:55.965 --> 38:57.183
You bet.

38:58.418 --> 39:00.253
(EVA CRYING)

39:00.976 --> 39:02.811
(CRYING): Daddy...

39:10.764 --> 39:12.221
(BELL SIGHS)

39:12.231 --> 39:13.930
You never had kids, right?

39:14.601 --> 39:16.903
No. Not to my knowledge.

39:18.505 --> 39:21.665
I got to wash up.
Why are kids always so sticky?

39:21.675 --> 39:24.701
It's mostly snot, and a bit of saliva.

39:24.711 --> 39:28.038
- Some sugar.
- It-it was a rhetorical question.

39:28.049 --> 39:30.452
(KIT LAUGHS)

39:34.565 --> 39:35.768
Robert Tuttle?

39:38.057 --> 39:40.383
Call me Bob. (CHUCKLES)

39:40.393 --> 39:42.295
And what's your name, pretty lady?

39:43.354 --> 39:45.780
Uh, Nurse Practitioner Nevin.

39:45.798 --> 39:48.457
- Ah.
- Donna's very eager to see you.

39:48.467 --> 39:50.727
Apparently, it's been a long time.

39:50.737 --> 39:52.629
(CHUCKLES) 30 years.

39:52.639 --> 39:56.399
I almost leaped out of my pants
when she reached out.

39:56.409 --> 39:59.313
Donna was my first real love.

40:00.547 --> 40:01.958
She was...

40:02.560 --> 40:05.075
- She was quite a beauty.
- Mm.

40:05.085 --> 40:09.172
I, uh... I guess we're both in
for a bit of a shock. (CHUCKLES)

40:10.056 --> 40:13.049
But I'm prepared for anything.

40:13.059 --> 40:15.484
- I'm a romantic at heart.
- Mm.

40:15.494 --> 40:17.654
I, uh, can't believe we have the chance

40:17.664 --> 40:19.967
to say a decent good-bye.

40:21.768 --> 40:25.160
("LANDSLIDE" BY FLEETWOOD MAC PLAYING)

40:25.170 --> 40:27.430
Would you look at that.

40:27.440 --> 40:29.476
She's playing our song.

40:34.481 --> 40:37.439
<i>♪ I took my love, took it down... ♪</i>

40:37.449 --> 40:39.442
You look great, honey.

40:39.452 --> 40:41.910
Oh, you're still a liar.

40:41.920 --> 40:44.647
I look like death, which is appropriate.

40:44.657 --> 40:48.685
(LAUGHS) Same old Donna.

40:48.695 --> 40:53.767
Oh... when we first met, I was so happy.

40:55.702 --> 40:57.960
Then you left me.

40:57.970 --> 41:01.531
(COUGHS) Destroyed me.

41:01.541 --> 41:06.803
You broke my heart, and...
you caused me so much pain.

41:06.813 --> 41:12.142
For 30 years, I've needed
to say something to you, Bob.

41:13.070 --> 41:15.879
Something I should have said
long before.

41:15.889 --> 41:20.683
<i>♪ Can I handle the seasons of my life? ♪</i>

41:20.693 --> 41:22.528
Go to hell.

41:25.130 --> 41:28.001
(DONNA LAUGHING)

41:33.373 --> 41:39.468
<i>♪ Well, I've been afraid
of changing 'cause I've... ♪</i>

41:40.324 --> 41:42.305
CONRAD: That's what she wanted to say?

41:42.315 --> 41:43.573
NIC: Yep.

41:43.583 --> 41:46.566
CONRAD (LAUGHS): Glad she got to say it.

41:47.185 --> 41:49.043
NIC: Do you still think I was wrong?

41:49.054 --> 41:51.381
<i>♪ Even children get older... ♪</i>

41:51.391 --> 41:53.720
Ah, seems to me we were both wrong.

41:54.642 --> 41:57.152
Well, we got through it.

41:57.162 --> 41:58.654
(NIC SIGHS)

41:59.471 --> 42:01.135
You're right.

42:04.570 --> 42:06.354
(SIGHS)

42:06.873 --> 42:10.911
I don't want us to regret
the things we haven't said.

42:12.612 --> 42:13.954
Me, either.

42:14.849 --> 42:17.289
There's still a lot
we need to talk about.

42:17.951 --> 42:20.264
After a fight, it's easier to let it go.

42:20.275 --> 42:21.686
- Yeah.
- Not talk about it.

42:21.697 --> 42:25.365
The same issues keep coming up
over and over again.

42:26.226 --> 42:31.788
♪ 'Cause I've built my life
around you... ♪

42:31.798 --> 42:34.591
(INHALES DEEPLY, EXHALES)

42:34.601 --> 42:36.759
It's been a long night.

42:36.769 --> 42:39.428
♪ Even children get older... ♪

42:39.438 --> 42:41.430
Yes.

42:41.440 --> 42:43.609
So, not now.

42:44.911 --> 42:47.636
Tomorrow? My place?

42:47.646 --> 42:49.973
I'll swing by before work.

42:49.983 --> 42:51.094
Perfect.

42:51.818 --> 42:56.412
♪ The landslide will bring you down ♪

42:56.422 --> 42:57.980
I love you.

42:57.990 --> 43:00.716
♪ And if you see my reflection ♪

43:00.726 --> 43:02.151
I love you, too.

43:02.161 --> 43:05.321
♪ In the snow-covered hills ♪

43:05.331 --> 43:09.392
♪ Well, the landslide
will bring you down ♪

43:09.402 --> 43:13.462
♪ Oh, the landslide ♪

43:13.472 --> 43:16.576
♪ Will bring it down. ♪

